        "header": "7Comprehensive Training Details",
        "images": [
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2603.24793/2603.24793v1/figures/images/training_efficiency.jpg",
                "caption": "Figure 6:Training efficiency comparison. Our per-modality LoRAs range from 200 steps (video detailing) to 15,000 steps (cut-on-action), with most spatially-aligned controls converging in approximately 3,000 steps. Even summing across all 13 trained LoRAs (∼{\\sim}55K steps total), the training budget is less than one-third of a single VACE training run (200K steps) and comparable to camera-specific methods like BulletTime (40K iterations). This efficiency stems from fine-tuning only existing weights via LoRA adapters on a frozen backbone, with no new layers to train from scratch.",
                "position": 2110
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "header": "8Small-to-Large Control Grid",
        "images": [
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2603.24793/2603.24793v1/figures/images/control_grid.jpg",
                "caption": "Figure 7:Small-to-large control grid, illustrated on a depth-guided example. The reference canvas resolution scales with information density: each highlighted cell in the reference (top row) maps to the corresponding region in the full-resolution target (bottom row). At2×2\\timesdownscale, one reference token covers2×22{\\times}2target tokens; at4×4\\times, one covers4×44{\\times}4. Sparser controls thus require fewer reference tokens, reducing self-attention cost and yielding 35–50% inference speedup at4×4\\timesdownscale.",
                "position": 2207
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "header": "9Extended Ablations",
        "images": [
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2603.24793/2603.24793v1/x2.png",
                "caption": "Figure 8:VBench average score vs. training steps for the depth LoRA. Performance rises steeply from 500 to 1,000 steps and plateaus beyond 2,000 steps.",
                "position": 2230
            },
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2603.24793/2603.24793v1/figures/images/supp_qualitative/strength_modulation.jpg",
                "caption": "Figure 9:Inference-time strength modulation for depth-guided generation. Each row shows four evenly-spaced frames.Top row:depth condition.Subsequent rows:outputs at global strength 0.0, 0.25, 0.5, and 1.0. At lower strengths the model respects the coarse scene layout while exercising creative freedom; at strength 1.0 the output closely follows the depth map.††footnotemark:",
                "position": 2240
            }
